entry.title: Fix first run service crash in combination with ROOL
entry.content:
Before this change, the run on os login feature (ROOL) would

trigger an app startup which then collides with the first run

setup (sets up settings like sync etc.). This condition that

an app must not launch before the first run setup was completed

is checked with a DCHECK in the `ProfileManager`.



This change triggers the first run setup via the `FirstRunService`

and makes the app launch wait until the setup is completed. For now

we accept that the user can cancel the setup and and relaunch it

without ROOL happening afterwards (this will be done in a follow-up).



Further, the ROOL notification is moved to the launched-callback

to make sure that the notification is not shown too early. The test

changes reflect this behavior change. The tests are also enabled

for Lacros now.

entry.title: Extension port: only unregister the BFCached frames after navigation
entry.content:
In https://crrev.com/c/4914116, we call `port_->CloseChannel()` when

the FrameTracker observes a navigation that puts a page into BFCache.



This may cause problem if the navigation is a prerendering activation

because of two issues:

1. In the current implementation, when a navigation happens, the port

will unregister the new frame unless it's a same-doc navigation or

BFCache restoration. So the port created during prerendering will not

work after activation.

2. Previously we will close the extension port when a navigation that

puts a page into BFCache is committed in the WebContents. This assumes

the port only has registers the frames from the BFCached page. This is

not true with prerendering.



In this CL, we make the following changes to resolve the two issues:

1. Change the UnregisterFrame check from

`!IsServedFromBackForwardCache()` to `!IsPageActivation()` so

prerendered frame won't be unregistered.

2. When a navigation puts a page into BFCache, unregister all the frames

under the BFCached frame instead of closing the channel.

entry.title: [QoS] Tweak SetCurrentThreadQualityOfService on Windows
entry.content:
In this change, SetCurrentThreadQualityOfService:



- No longer uses GetProcAddress to find SetThreadInformation, as this

function was added in Windows 8. This removes unneeded contention on

the loader lock along with the associated complexity.

- No longer checks the OS version before use; instead, we trust that

versions of Windows prior to Windows 10, version 1709 will ignore a

call to SetThreadInformation with an unsupported

THREAD_INFORMATION_CLASS. The motivation for this is that the OS check

was implicated in renderer startup hangs, as it requires resolving a

delayload to reach the Windows registry. The OS version check is now

only done to suppress the debug log message in case of failure, as

failure is expected on versions of Windows prior to 1709.

entry.title: Reland "[dPWA] Show origin in web app title bar when navigating ..."
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 9c83a3fdfaf3cabeb0f8d1b55ac543b54c26b7af



The original CL caused browser tests to fail even through there were no

changes that impacted those tests in an obvious way. See

crbug.com/1488734 for details. The failures could have been caused by

changes in animation delay and timing, which the reverted CL did modify.



Patch 8 fixes the test failures by replacing usages of RunUntilIdle with

a view visibility waiter to more reliably wait for the view in question

to become visible.

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4909892/7..8



Original change's description:

> [dPWA] Show origin in web app title bar when navigating across origins

>

> When navigating in a web app window between different origins that are

> within the app's extended scope (using scope_extensions), the user needs

> to be kept aware of their security context. As a CCT UI is no longer

> displayed when navigating within extended scope, this CL modifies the

> title bar origin text both in terms of what is shown and when it is

> shown.

>

> Previous behavior:

> - Always show origin of start URL.

> - Shows text when the app window launches or when theme color changes.

> - Does not show text when a CCT UI is also shown.

> - Except when theme color changes.

>

> New behavior (with feature flag enabled):

> - Shows origin of current committed web content instead of always

> showing origin of the app's start url.

> - Shows origin when navigating to a different origin.

> - Even when a CCT UI is shown.

entry.title: Improve backdrop filter calculations in SkiaRenderer
entry.content:
Pulls all of the bounds analysis for how to clip the output and input

of a backdrop filter into the CalculateRPDQParams function. Improves

the calculations for the `filter_bounds` value to be tighter for

backdrop filters since their output is always restricted.



Optimizes more cases to have backdrop output restricted by just a

clip instead of introducing an image filter node at the end. Switches

the input cropping node from a no-op Offset(0,0) to a proper `Crop`

that can define the boundary tilemode to apply (kClamp). This

actually fixes the behavior in the backdrop-offset unit test. It also

makes it possible to easily experiment with using mirror tiling for

content that is off screen.



Re-organizes some of the logic for clipping or clearing the backdrop

correctly with and without the above staging flag.

entry.title: android: explicitly destroy the stencil framebuffer.
entry.content:
gl::GLContext holds offscreen surfaces now. However, they are not

destroyed until very end...until the context is actually destroyed.



It's OK in most of the cases, but it is not good in case of

the AwGLSurfaceExternalStencil that subclasses the AwGLSurface and that

creates stencil framebuffers that has to be destroyed on a correct

context.



Given that surface is also offscreen one (changed in

https://crrev.com/c/4942195), gl::GLContext holds it and it's not

guaranteed that particular context will be current. As a result, no

context/wrong context crash may happen.



To mitigate the issue, add a helper stencil framebuffer destruction

method that AwGLSurfaceExternalStencil implements, and which is called

when OutputSurfaceProviderWebView no longer needs the surface.
